result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica L Stensberg was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/ Intent-Amphetamine/Methamphetamine/etc.(>3-10g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(e)2.
  • Neglecting a Child (Specified Harm Did Not Occur) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(2).
  • Neglecting a Child (Specified Harm Did Not Occur) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

records.addlTxt:
3:17 PM Defendant Jessica L Stensberg in court.  Attorney David R. Knaapen in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Defendant states she is not eligible for Public Defender, but filled out a request for court appointed counsel and mailed it. Court will proceed with preliminary hearing today.
John Matthews is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Knaapen. He is an Investigative Sargeant with the Wood County Sheriff's Department. On 3/3/22, he executed a search warrant in the Town of Rudolph. He states who was at the residence and the defendant was one of those people. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom. He testifies as to drugs and drug paraphernalia found in the residence. He learned that defendant had been convicted of a drug offense in 2016. The substances were tested and they tested positive for methamphetamine. He located in the garage bags of white powdery substance and it tested positive for methamphetamine. He testifies as to the total weight of methamphetamine and he believes the amount indicated that it was intended to be distributed.
Attorney Knaapen asks Court take judicial notice of Wood County case 15CF438, a prior drug conviction.
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the defendant committed it. Bound over for further proceedings. Bond is continued.
Arraignment scheduled for April 18, 2022 at 10:00 am.
